---
import OpsLayout from '../layouts/OpsLayout.astro';
---

<OpsLayout title="FAQ">

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <!-- PAGE HEADER                                 -->
  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <header class="page-header">
    <div class="header-hud-tl" aria-hidden="true"></div>
    <p class="header-eyebrow">[ OPERATIVE DATABASE ]</p>
    <h1 class="header-title">FREQUENTLY ASKED</h1>
    <p class="header-sub">
      <span class="header-count">NEW PLAYER BRIEFING</span>
      &nbsp;·&nbsp; Common questions before you drop in
    </p>
  </header>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <!-- FAQ SECTIONS                                -->
  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="faq-root">

    <!-- BASICS -->
    <section class="faq-section">
      <div class="faq-section-header">
        <span class="faq-section-label">01</span>
        <span class="faq-section-title">THE BASICS</span>
      </div>

      <dl class="faq-list">

        <div class="faq-item">
          <dt class="faq-question" tabindex="0">
            <span>What even is Zombies mode?</span>
            <span class="faq-chevron" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
          </dt>
          <dd class="faq-answer">
            <p>Zombies is a cooperative survival mode built into Call of Duty games. You and up to three teammates hold off endless waves of undead that get tougher every round. The goal is to survive as long as possible — or, on certain maps, complete a multi-step Easter Egg quest.</p>
            <p>It started as a bonus mini-game in <em>World at War</em> (2008) and grew into its own full storyline spanning six games, with dedicated maps, characters, and lore.</p>
          </dd>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <dt class="faq-question" tabindex="0">
            <span>What is Pack-a-Punch (PaP)?</span>
            <span class="faq-chevron" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
          </dt>
          <dd class="faq-answer">
            <p>Pack-a-Punch is a machine found on every map that upgrades your weapon for 2,500 points. It boosts damage, ammo capacity, and fire rate, and gives the gun a new name. Most high-round strategies revolve around getting PaP as early as possible.</p>
            <p>On many maps the machine is locked behind a puzzle or sequence of steps — unlocking it is usually your first objective.</p>
          </dd>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <dt class="faq-question" tabindex="0">
            <span>What is the Mystery Box?</span>
            <span class="faq-chevron" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
          </dt>
          <dd class="faq-answer">
            <p>The Mystery Box is a glowing crate scattered around each map that gives you a random weapon for 950 points. It's the only way to obtain Wonder Weapons on most maps. The box relocates after several uses — you'll hear Samantha laughing and see a beam of light to find its new location.</p>
          </dd>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <dt class="faq-question" tabindex="0">
            <span>What are Perks?</span>
            <span class="faq-chevron" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
          </dt>
          <dd class="faq-answer">
            <p>Perks are permanent upgrades you buy from vending machines placed around the map. Core perks you'll see on almost every map:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Juggernog</strong> — doubles your health. Buy this first, every game.</li>
              <li><strong>Speed Cola</strong> — cuts reload time in half.</li>
              <li><strong>Double Tap</strong> — doubles fire rate and damage.</li>
              <li><strong>Quick Revive</strong> — lets you self-revive once in solo, or revive teammates faster in co-op.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>You lose perks when you go down (unless you have Quick Revive active in solo). There is no way to permanently keep them — that's part of the loop.</p>
          </dd>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <dt class="faq-question" tabindex="0">
            <span>What are Wonder Weapons?</span>
            <span class="faq-chevron" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
          </dt>
          <dd class="faq-answer">
            <p>Wonder Weapons are unique, map-specific guns that behave unlike anything in multiplayer — ray guns, staffs, bows, wands, wonder weapons fire beams, summon lightning, or teleport zombies. Many can be upgraded via Easter Egg steps into even more powerful versions.</p>
            <p>The Ray Gun is the most iconic and appears in the Mystery Box on every map.</p>
          </dd>
        </div>

      </dl>
    </section>

    <!-- GAMEPLAY -->
    <section class="faq-section">
      <div class="faq-section-header">
        <span class="faq-section-label">02</span>
        <span class="faq-section-title">GAMEPLAY</span>
      </div>

      <dl class="faq-list">

        <div class="faq-item">
          <dt class="faq-question" tabindex="0">
            <span>How do points work?</span>
            <span class="faq-chevron" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
          </dt>
          <dd class="faq-answer">
            <p>Points (called Essence in newer games) are your currency. You earn them by hitting and killing zombies:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>10 pts per bullet hit</li>
              <li>50 pts per melee hit</li>
              <li>100 pts for a kill</li>
              <li>130 pts for a headshot kill</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Spend points on wall-buy weapons, perks, the Mystery Box, door openings, and Pack-a-Punch. Don't hoard — spent points compound into better gear faster than saving them.</p>
          </dd>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <dt class="faq-question" tabindex="0">
            <span>What is "training" and why does everyone talk about it?</span>
            <span class="faq-chevron" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
          </dt>
          <dd class="faq-answer">
            <p>Training (or "running a train") means leading a large horde of zombies in a circle around an open area so they stack into a tight clump. You then gun down the whole clump in one pass. It's the most reliable high-round technique because it prevents zombies from surrounding you.</p>
            <p>Every map has at least one good training area. The maps page notes these in the strategy section of each guide.</p>
          </dd>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <dt class="faq-question" tabindex="0">
            <span>Does progress carry over between sessions?</span>
            <span class="faq-chevron" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
          </dt>
          <dd class="faq-answer">
            <p>No. Each session starts fresh from Round 1 with your starting pistol and no perks. Easter Egg quest progress does <em>not</em> carry over either — you must complete the entire Easter Egg in a single session.</p>
            <p>Some games introduced a Directed Mode (BO6 onwards) which checkpoints narrative Easter Eggs across sessions, but classic Survival is always a fresh run.</p>
          </dd>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <dt class="faq-question" tabindex="0">
            <span>Is solo harder than co-op?</span>
            <span class="faq-chevron" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
          </dt>
          <dd class="faq-answer">
            <p>Different, not strictly harder. In solo, you get a free Quick Revive that lets you self-revive three times before it's consumed. Zombie count and health are scaled to one player, so the horde is smaller. Many players find high rounds easier in solo because you control the entire map and don't have teammates opening doors at bad times.</p>
            <p>Easter Eggs in co-op require coordination but some steps are solo-only by design — check the guide for each map.</p>
          </dd>
        </div>

      </dl>
    </section>

    <!-- EASTER EGGS & STORY -->
    <section class="faq-section">
      <div class="faq-section-header">
        <span class="faq-section-label">03</span>
        <span class="faq-section-title">EASTER EGGS &amp; STORY</span>
      </div>

      <dl class="faq-list">

        <div class="faq-item">
          <dt class="faq-question" tabindex="0">
            <span>What are Easter Eggs?</span>
            <span class="faq-chevron" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
          </dt>
          <dd class="faq-answer">
            <p>Easter Eggs are hidden multi-step quests built into each map. Completing them advances the overarching story and usually rewards you with a unique cutscene, a powerful weapon upgrade, or achievement/trophy. They range from short side steps (a few minutes) to full Main Quests that take hours and require specific gear and crew coordination.</p>
            <p>Maps on this site mark Easter Eggs as <strong>MQ</strong> (Main Quest present) and rate their difficulty from 1–5.</p>
          </dd>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <dt class="faq-question" tabindex="0">
            <span>Do I need to do Easter Eggs to enjoy the game?</span>
            <span class="faq-chevron" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
          </dt>
          <dd class="faq-answer">
            <p>Not at all. Pure survival — getting to high rounds without touching the Easter Egg — is a completely valid way to play and how most people start. Easter Eggs are optional content for players who want the lore or a challenge.</p>
            <p>That said, some maps are designed around the Easter Egg progression and feel more purposeful when you know what you're building toward. The map guides note which maps reward a story-first approach.</p>
          </dd>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <dt class="faq-question" tabindex="0">
            <span>What order should I play the story maps?</span>
            <span class="faq-chevron" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
          </dt>
          <dd class="faq-answer">
            <p>The original Aether storyline (WaW through BO4) has a canonical order, but it isn't the same as release order. A good starting sequence for story purposes:</p>
            <ol>
              <li><strong>Nacht der Untoten</strong> — the origin point, no story but sets tone</li>
              <li><strong>Kino der Toten</strong> — introduces the four classic characters properly</li>
              <li><strong>Ascension → Call of the Dead → Shangri-La → Moon</strong> — BO1 arc</li>
              <li>BO2 maps → BO3 maps (Origins is the BO3 prologue) → BO4's Blood of the Dead, Tag der Toten</li>
            </ol>
            <p>If story isn't your priority, start with whichever map looks most fun. The Kronorium on this site charts the full timeline.</p>
          </dd>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <dt class="faq-question" tabindex="0">
            <span>There are two storylines? What's the difference?</span>
            <span class="faq-chevron" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
          </dt>
          <dd class="faq-answer">
            <p>Yes. After BO4, Treyarch soft-rebooted the universe:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Aether Storyline (WaW – BO4):</strong> Richtofen, Dempsey, Nikolai, Takeo. Multiversal chaos, Aether dimension, Element 115, Samantha Maxis as the villain/puppet. Concluded in BO4.</li>
              <li><strong>Dark Aether Storyline (Cold War – present):</strong> New characters, set in a single timeline in the 1980s–90s. CIA's Requiem vs. Soviet Omega Group. Different tone, more grounded (relatively).</li>
            </ul>
            <p>The two stories are not connected. You can enjoy either independently.</p>
          </dd>
        </div>

      </dl>
    </section>

    <!-- GETTING STARTED -->
    <section class="faq-section">
      <div class="faq-section-header">
        <span class="faq-section-label">04</span>
        <span class="faq-section-title">GETTING STARTED</span>
      </div>

      <dl class="faq-list">

        <div class="faq-item">
          <dt class="faq-question" tabindex="0">
            <span>What's the best map for a complete beginner?</span>
            <span class="faq-chevron" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
          </dt>
          <dd class="faq-answer">
            <p>Depends on what you have access to and what you want:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Kino der Toten (BO1)</strong> — the classic choice. Simple layout, great training area in the theater, forgiving for solo beginners.</li>
              <li><strong>Ascension (BO1)</strong> — bigger map, more room to train, slightly more complex but very learnable.</li>
              <li><strong>Die Maschine (Cold War)</strong> — best entry point for the Dark Aether era. Clean tutorial-friendly design.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Avoid maps rated 4+ difficulty for setup until you're comfortable with the core loop.</p>
          </dd>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <dt class="faq-question" tabindex="0">
            <span>What should I do first every round?</span>
            <span class="faq-chevron" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
          </dt>
          <dd class="faq-answer">
            <p>A reliable early-game priority order:</p>
            <ol>
              <li>Kill zombies with your starting pistol, aim for headshots, keep one zombie alive at end of round to buy time.</li>
              <li>Open doors toward the Pack-a-Punch machine and toward Juggernog.</li>
              <li>Buy Juggernog first — it's the most important perk in the game.</li>
              <li>Hit the Mystery Box or buy a wall weapon to replace your pistol.</li>
              <li>Pack-a-Punch your best weapon as soon as you can afford 2,500 pts.</li>
            </ol>
          </dd>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <dt class="faq-question" tabindex="0">
            <span>What does "keep a crawler" mean?</span>
            <span class="faq-chevron" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
          </dt>
          <dd class="faq-answer">
            <p>At the end of each round you can shoot a zombie in the legs to cripple it — it becomes a slow-moving crawler instead of killing it. The round doesn't end until all zombies are dead, so a crawler gives you unlimited time to buy perks, open doors, or run to the box without the next wave starting. Essential for setup rounds.</p>
            <p>Grenades also create crawlers reliably. The crawler will eventually die on its own after a few minutes, so don't forget about it.</p>
          </dd>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <dt class="faq-question" tabindex="0">
            <span>What round is considered "good" for a first-time player?</span>
            <span class="faq-chevron" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
          </dt>
          <dd class="faq-answer">
            <p>Round 20 is a common first milestone — reaching it means you understand the core loop. Round 30+ means you have solid fundamentals. Round 50 is a benchmark for experienced players. Round 100 is a dedicated high-round grind that takes several hours even for veterans.</p>
            <p>Don't chase numbers early. Focus on understanding <em>why</em> you went down each time, not just how far you got.</p>
          </dd>
        </div>

      </dl>
    </section>

  </div><!-- .faq-root -->

</OpsLayout>

<script>
  document.querySelectorAll<HTMLElement>('.faq-question').forEach(question => {
    function toggle() {
      const item   = question.closest<HTMLElement>('.faq-item')!;
      const answer = item.querySelector<HTMLElement>('.faq-answer')!;
      const chevron = question.querySelector<HTMLElement>('.faq-chevron')!;
      const open   = item.classList.toggle('is-open');
      chevron.textContent = open ? '−' : '+';
      answer.style.maxHeight = open ? answer.scrollHeight + 'px' : '0';
    }

    question.addEventListener('click', toggle);
    question.addEventListener('keydown', e => {
      if (e.key === 'Enter' || e.key === ' ') { e.preventDefault(); toggle(); }
    });
  });
</script>

<style>
  /* ════════════════════════════════════════════════ */
  /* Page header (shared pattern)                     */
  /* ════════════════════════════════════════════════ */
  .page-header {
    position: relative;
    margin-bottom: 48px;
    padding-bottom: 28px;
    border-bottom: 1px solid #1e2028;
  }

  .header-hud-tl {
    position: absolute;
    top: 0; left: 0;
    width: 24px; height: 24px;
    border-top: 2px solid #e07b2a;
    border-left: 2px solid #e07b2a;
    opacity: 0.6;
  }

  .header-eyebrow {
    font-family: 'IBM Plex Mono', monospace;
    font-size: 10px;
    letter-spacing: 0.28em;
    color: #e07b2a;
    opacity: 0.8;
    margin: 0 0 10px 0;
    padding-left: 4px;
  }

  .header-title {
    font-family: 'Rajdhani', sans-serif;
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: clamp(40px, 5vw, 72px);
    line-height: 1;
    color: #dde1ea;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    margin: 0 0 12px 0;
  }

  .header-sub {
    font-family: 'IBM Plex Mono', monospace;
    font-size: 11px;
    color: #4a4e5a;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .header-count { color: #e07b2a; }

  /* ════════════════════════════════════════════════ */
  /* FAQ root                                         */
  /* ════════════════════════════════════════════════ */
  .faq-root {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 48px;
    max-width: 860px;
  }

  /* ════════════════════════════════════════════════ */
  /* Section header                                   */
  /* ════════════════════════════════════════════════ */
  .faq-section-header {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 16px;
    margin-bottom: 20px;
    padding-bottom: 14px;
    border-bottom: 1px solid #1e2028;
  }

  .faq-section-label {
    font-family: 'IBM Plex Mono', monospace;
    font-size: 11px;
    letter-spacing: 0.2em;
    color: #e07b2a;
    opacity: 0.7;
    flex-shrink: 0;
  }

  .faq-section-title {
    font-family: 'Rajdhani', sans-serif;
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: 18px;
    letter-spacing: 0.18em;
    color: #dde1ea;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  /* ════════════════════════════════════════════════ */
  /* FAQ list                                         */
  /* ════════════════════════════════════════════════ */
  .faq-list {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 2px;
  }

  /* ════════════════════════════════════════════════ */
  /* FAQ item                                         */
  /* ════════════════════════════════════════════════ */
  .faq-item {
    border: 1px solid #1e2028;
    background: #0f1114;
    overflow: hidden;
    transition: border-color 0.15s;
  }

  .faq-item:hover,
  .faq-item.is-open {
    border-color: #252830;
  }

  .faq-item.is-open {
    border-left: 2px solid #e07b2a;
  }

  /* ════════════════════════════════════════════════ */
  /* Question row                                     */
  /* ════════════════════════════════════════════════ */
  .faq-question {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: space-between;
    gap: 16px;
    padding: 16px 20px;
    cursor: pointer;
    list-style: none;
    font-family: 'Rajdhani', sans-serif;
    font-weight: 600;
    font-size: 16px;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    color: #c4c8d4;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    user-select: none;
    outline: none;
    transition: color 0.15s;
  }

  .faq-question:focus-visible {
    outline: 1px solid #e07b2a;
    outline-offset: -1px;
  }

  .faq-item.is-open .faq-question,
  .faq-question:hover {
    color: #dde1ea;
  }

  .faq-chevron {
    font-family: 'IBM Plex Mono', monospace;
    font-size: 18px;
    color: #e07b2a;
    flex-shrink: 0;
    line-height: 1;
    transition: color 0.15s;
  }

  /* ════════════════════════════════════════════════ */
  /* Answer panel                                     */
  /* ════════════════════════════════════════════════ */
  .faq-answer {
    max-height: 0;
    overflow: hidden;
    transition: max-height 0.3s ease;
  }

  .faq-answer p,
  .faq-answer ul,
  .faq-answer ol {
    font-family: 'Rajdhani', sans-serif;
    font-size: 15px;
    line-height: 1.65;
    color: #8a8f9e;
    margin: 0 0 12px;
  }

  .faq-answer p:last-child,
  .faq-answer ul:last-child,
  .faq-answer ol:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  .faq-answer > p:first-child,
  .faq-answer > ul:first-child,
  .faq-answer > ol:first-child {
    padding-top: 0;
  }

  .faq-answer ul,
  .faq-answer ol {
    padding-left: 20px;
  }

  .faq-answer li {
    margin-bottom: 6px;
  }

  .faq-answer strong {
    color: #c4c8d4;
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .faq-answer em {
    color: #e07b2a;
    font-style: normal;
  }

  /* inner padding wrapper — keeps transition clean */
  .faq-answer > * {
    padding: 0 20px 20px;
  }

  .faq-answer p:first-child,
  .faq-answer ul:first-child,
  .faq-answer ol:first-child {
    padding-top: 4px;
  }

  /* ════════════════════════════════════════════════ */
  /* Responsive                                       */
  /* ════════════════════════════════════════════════ */
  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .faq-question { font-size: 14px; padding: 14px 16px; }
    .faq-answer > * { padding: 0 16px 16px; }
    .faq-answer p,
    .faq-answer ul,
    .faq-answer ol { font-size: 14px; }
  }
</style>
